    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-06-18T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-06-18T11:00:00-05:00" n="896"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d896">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.248/580: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Turkey</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Ankara</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-06-18T19:00:00+03:00"
                            >June 18, 1942—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 9:42 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>632. My 625, June 18, 2 p.m. Numan Bey<note n="96" xml:id="d896fn96">Numan
                        Menemenğlu, Secretary General of the Turkish Foreign Office.</note>
                    telephoned me this morning that a lengthy telegram had been received last night
                    by the semi-official Anatolian Agency from Berlin charging Turk neutrality had
                    been intentionally violated by our planes on outward bound as well as return
                    flight. In connection with publication of telegram from Berlin Numan Bey said he
                    had instructed Anatolian to add a full statement to effect State Department had
                    informed Turk Ambassador in Washington and the United States Ambassador in
                    Ankara had informed Turk Foreign Office specific instructions had been issued to
                    pilots not to fly over Turk territory and that they had complied with their
                    orders excepting in case of individual planes which had been compelled to make
                    forced landings in Turkey and that in consequence any violation of Turk
                    neutrality had been wholly unintentional and occasioned only by necessity. Also
                    interrogation by Turk military authorities of pilots now in Ankara fully
                    confirmed statements made by the United States Ambassador in Ankara and to Turk
                    Ambassador in Washington and Turkish Government was accordingly entirely
                    satisfied there had been no intentional violation of Turkish neutrality.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
